Diversity may provide a variety of viewpoints and ideas to a group or organization, increase creativity and innovation, and contribute to the development of an inclusive culture. However, it may also provide disadvantages, such as communication difficulties and the possibility of violence between diverse groups. Diversity is more likely to be advantageous in circumstances requiring a variety of viewpoints and ideas, such as problem-solving and decision-making. Additionally, it may be advantageous when a varied group or organization is better equipped to serve a diverse community. In contrast, diversity may be least advantageous when a homogenous group is required for a particular job or when a single opinion is more significant than a variety of views. It may also be less advantageous in circumstances where cultural competence is lacking or if individuals are unwilling to learn from or collaborate with others from diverse backgrounds. 